---

## 9. Incident Response (Lightweight)

When an incident occurs:

1) Acknowledge it
2) Update the status page if customer-facing
3) Capture basic notes while fresh
4) Fix or mitigate
5) Add short post-incident summary

Post-incident notes should include:

- What happened
- User impact
- Root cause (as best as known)
- Fix applied
- Follow-up action items

Keep it short but honest.

---

## 10. Support and User Assistance

If a user reports a problem, try to collect:

- timestamp or rough window
- their email or user ID
- what they were trying to do
- screenshot if available
- any error or request ID they saw

Helpful app features (if implemented):

- impersonate user safely
- admin panel to view recent errors
- per-tenant feature flags

Always avoid:

- asking for passwords
- sending sensitive logs via email
- exposing other users' data while debugging

---

## 11. Security and Reliability Checklists

This project also includes:

- `SECURITY_CHECKLIST.md`
- `RELIABILITY_CHECKLIST.md`

Before major releases, review both documents intentionally.

They exist to make problems less likely and recovery faster when something does happen.

---

## 12. Philosophy

The goal of this operational guide is simple:

- keep customers calm
- keep you calm
- turn surprises into routine steps

A small amount of structure here saves a huge amount of pain later. This file should evolve as the system grows. Treat it as a living field manual rather than a static document.